Single-file change to `apps/desktop/src/components/terminal/Terminal.tsx`. Per the user's chosen approach, this is the **no-dependency** fix ŌĆö no `tauri-plugin-clipboard-manager`, no `pnpm install`. Uses the same `navigator.clipboard` API the existing `Ctrl+Shift+C` handler already relies on.

### Change 1 ŌĆö add a `Ctrl+C` branch to `attachCustomKeyEventHandler` (after the existing `Ctrl+Shift+C` branch, ~line 300)

Windows Terminal / VS Code convention: copy when a selection exists, otherwise send SIGINT.

```ts
// Ctrl+C: copy the selection if there is one (Windows Terminal / VS Code
// convention); otherwise fall through so xterm sends SIGINT (\x03) to the PTY.
// Plain Ctrl+C had no binding before ŌĆö it always sent SIGINT even with a
// selection active (#171).
if (e.type === 'keydown' && e.ctrlKey && !e.shiftKey && (e.key === 'c' || e.key === 'C')) {
  const selection = xterm.getSelection();
  if (selection) {
    navigator.clipboard.writeText(selection).catch(() => { /* clipboard write blocked */ });
    return false; // handled ŌĆö do NOT also send SIGINT
  }
  return true; // no selection ŌĆö let xterm send SIGINT as usual
}
```

### Change 2 ŌĆö add `Ctrl+V` and `Ctrl+Shift+V` paste branches (same handler)

#155 deleted these on the premise that xterm.js's native `paste` DOM-event listener owns paste. Per #171's analysis that native path does not fire reliably inside the Tauri WebView2, so read the clipboard explicitly and call `xterm.paste()` (which still honors the shell's bracketed-paste mode).

```ts
// Ctrl+V / Ctrl+Shift+V: paste from the clipboard. xterm.js's native paste
// DOM event does not fire reliably inside the Tauri WebView2 (#171), so read
// the clipboard explicitly. The capture-phase `paste` suppressor registered
// below guarantees this stays the SINGLE paste path ŌĆö without it a WebView2
// that *does* dispatch the native event would double-paste (the #155 bug).
if (e.type === 'keydown' && e.ctrlKey && (e.key === 'v' || e.key === 'V')) {
  navigator.clipboard.readText()
    .then((text) => { if (text) xterm.paste(text); })
    .catch(() => { /* clipboard read blocked in this webview ŌĆö nothing to paste */ });
  return false;
}
```

Note this branch intentionally matches both `Ctrl+V` and `Ctrl+Shift+V` (no `e.shiftKey` discriminator) ŌĆö both should paste.

### Change 3 ŌĆö capture-phase `paste` suppressor on the container element

This is the belt-and-suspenders that resolves the tension with #155. A `paste` listener registered on the **parent `container`** with `{ capture: true }` runs in the capture phase ŌĆö *before* the event reaches xterm's helper textarea and its bubble-phase listener. Calling `stopPropagation()` there means xterm's internal paste listener never sees the event, so even if WebView2 *does* dispatch a native `paste`, it cannot double-write. Our Ctrl+V keydown handler above is the only paste path.

Register immediately after `xterm.open(container)` (~line 267):

```ts
// Belt-and-suspenders for #155: if this WebView2 dispatches a native `paste`
// event on xterm's helper textarea, xterm's built-in listener would write the
// pasted text a second time. A capture-phase listener on the parent fires
// before the event reaches the textarea, so stopPropagation() prevents xterm
// from ever seeing it. Our Ctrl+V keydown handler is the single paste path.
// NOTE: if a right-click "Paste" context-menu item is ever added to the
// terminal, this unconditional suppressor must become a guarded one.
const suppressNativePaste = (ev: ClipboardEvent) => {
  ev.preventDefault();
  ev.stopPropagation();
};
container.addEventListener('paste', suppressNativePaste, true);
```

Add the matching cleanup in the effect's existing teardown function (the `return () => { ... }` block, ~line 383), alongside the existing disposal logic:

```ts
container.removeEventListener('paste', suppressNativePaste, true);
```

### Notes / scope boundaries

- The existing `Ctrl+Shift+C` branch is untouched and keeps working (regression-checked below).
- No new dependencies, no `Cargo.toml` / `package.json` / capabilities changes. The `tauri-plugin-clipboard-manager` robustness upgrade from the issue body is deliberately deferred (it needs an elevated `pnpm install` that can't run on this machine ŌĆö same blocker that deferred #161).
- Residual risk, to be confirmed by the smoke test: if WebView2 blocks `navigator.clipboard.readText()` entirely, Ctrl+V still won't paste ŌĆö but Ctrl+C copy (`writeText`) and Ctrl+Shift+C will work, and the terminal is no worse than the current shipped state (which has no handler at all). The `.catch()` keeps a blocked read from throwing an unhandled rejection.
- `e.key` is matched case-insensitively (`'c'`/`'C'`, `'v'`/`'V'`) to mirror the existing `Ctrl+Shift+K` branch's pattern and survive Caps Lock.
